a is followed by an antarala and the sanctuary in the main temple of Brihadeeswarar, which has an incredible architecture. The main draw of the 216-foot-tall, Dravidian-styled tower with 13 levels that overlook the sanctum is the temple. The vimana is proud of its enormous, 80-ton weight. According to legend, a 2 km long ramp was constructed to transport and position the Sikhara on the mountain. Sikhara never casts a shadow that hits the floor. The vimana from the temple is much larger than the temple tower at the entrance, which is unusual for Hindu temples. Exquisite mural paintings once graced the interior walls of the maha mandapa of the temple, but they disintegrated over time owing to neglect. Some of these murals can be found in the museum, which is located in the temple's southern hallway. The walls of the circumambulatory passage's Chola murals had some badly affected sections. Around 400 years ago, the Tanjore Nayak monarchs replaced them with a few of their unique artworks. The 108 dance positions of Bharatanatyam, the traditional dance of Tamil Nadu, are etched on the exterior wall of the upper level. 3. Vijayanagar Fort You only have to travel 2 km to reach this amazing palace from the Brihadeeswara temple. In the year 1550 AD, Nayak kings and certain Maratha kings collaborated to construct this magnificent fort. The castle includes a library, an outstanding art gallery, and the Tanjore Palace, Sangeetha Mahal, etc. Additionally, a part of the fort complex is the Shiva Ganga Gardens. The fort still conveys the strength and grandeur that it must have once held, despite being largely demolished. Time to visit:7:00 AM - 1:00 PM & 3:00 PM - 6:00 PM 4. Airavatesvara Temple Among the many Shiva temples in Thanjavur is the Airavatesvara temple, which is situated near Darasuram. According to tradition, Lord Indra's white elephant, Airavata, came here to pray to Lord Shiva in order to lift a curse placed on him by Rishi Durvasa. Yama, the god of death, is claime