le in 1025 CE, Gangaikonda Cholapuram was designated as the Cholas' capital, and it remained there for about 250 years. The famed Brihadeeswarar Temple is located in this medieval town. Rajendra Chola I, Rajaraja Chola's son and successor, constructed it. The "Great Living Chola Temples" UNESCO World Heritage Site includes this temple. Rajendra Chola built this temple following his impressive triumphs in Northern India. After being crowned, he changed his name from Madurantakam to Rajendra, but for a while, he shared the throne with his father, Rajaraja-I. The Brihadisvara Temple in GangaiKondaCholapuram is thought to be a replica of the original, which was constructed by Rajaraja Chola, Rajendra Chola's father. The largest Shiva Lingam in the Southern region of India is said to be located in this temple. For more than two centuries, Gangaikonda Cholapuram served as the capital of the Chola Empire. This location of tremendous historical significance highlighted the start of one of the greatest reigns in Southern Indian history. The once-famous historical city is now only a little village, with the Lord Siva temple serving as a reminder of its once-proud past splendor. Gangaikonda Cholapuram, which is sometimes compared to Thanjavur, another outstanding Chola city, is a wonderful destination to discover and uncover its heritage, magnificence, and elaborate marvels and tales, carefully buried deep in history. 2. Brihadeeswarar Temple Brihadeeswarar Temple is regarded as the most elaborate example of South Indian temple architecture. Raja Raja Chola I constructed the Brihadeeswara temple, one of the city's most significant attractions. It was allegedly built as a celebration of the Chola Kingdom's victory and is now a world heritage site. It is also referred to as Periya Kovil or Peruvudaiyar Kovil. The temple is a component of the "Great Living Chola Temples'' UNESCO World Heritage Site. Brihadeeswarar Temple also referred to as The Big Temple, is a temple devoted to 