ja Chola's son and successor, constructed it. The "Great Living Chola Temples" UNESCO World Heritage Site includes this temple. Rajendra Chola built this temple following his impressive triumphs in Northern India. After being crowned, he changed his name from Madurantakam to Rajendra, but for a while, he shared the throne with his father, Rajaraja-I. The Brihadisvara Temple in GangaiKondaCholapuram is thought to be a replica of the original, which was constructed by Rajaraja Chola, Rajendra Chola's father. The largest Shiva Lingam in the Southern region of India is said to be located in this temple. For more than two centuries, Gangaikonda Cholapuram served as the capital of the Chola Empire. This location of tremendous historical significance highlighted the start of one of the greatest reigns in Southern Indian history. The once-famous historical city is now only a little village, with the Lord Siva temple serving as a reminder of its once-proud past splendor. Gangaikonda Cholapuram, which is sometimes compared to Thanjavur, another outstanding Chola city, is a wonderful destination to discover and uncover its heritage, magnificence, and elaborate marvels and tales, carefully buried deep in history. 2. Brihadeeswarar Temple Brihadeeswarar Temple is regarded as the most elaborate example of South Indian temple architecture. Raja Raja Chola I constructed the Brihadeeswara temple, one of the city's most significant attractions. It was allegedly built as a celebration of the Chola Kingdom's victory and is now a world heritage site. It is also referred to as Periya Kovil or Peruvudaiyar Kovil. The temple is a component of the "Great Living Chola Temples'' UNESCO World Heritage Site. Brihadeeswarar Temple also referred to as The Big Temple, is a temple devoted to Lord Shiva that is renowned for its size and exquisite artwork. The temple is made up of an entry tower and the main temple complex that is spread out across a 33,000-square-foot square foot plot of land. A 12-foot-tall monolithic idol with an artistically carved Nandi Mandapa marks the beginning of the temple's interior. A huge mandapa is followed by an antarala and the sanctuary in the main temple of Brihadeeswarar, which has an incredible architecture. The main draw of the 216-foot-tall, Dravidian-styled tower with 13 levels that overlook the sanctum is the temple. The vimana is proud of its enormous, 80-ton weight. According to legend, a 2 km long ramp was constructed to transport and position the Sikhara on the mountain. Sikhara never casts a shadow that hits the floor. The vimana from the temple is much larger than the temple tower at the entrance, which is unusual for Hindu temples. Exquisite mural paintings once graced the interior walls of the maha mandapa of the temple, but they disintegrated over time owing to neglect. Some of these murals can be found in the museum, which is located in the temple's southern hallway. The walls of the circumambulatory passage's Chola murals had some badly affected sections. Around 400 years ago, the Tanjore Nayak monarchs replaced them with a few of their unique artworks. The 108 dance positions of Bharatanatyam, the traditional dance of Tamil Nadu, are etched on the exterior wall of the upper level. 3. Vijayanagar Fort You only have to travel 2 km to reach this amazing palace from the Brihadeeswara temple. In the year 1550 AD, Nayak kings and certain Maratha kings collaborated to construct this magnificent fort. The castle includes a library, an outstanding art gallery, and the Tanjore Palace, Sangeetha Mahal, etc. Additionally, a part of the fort complex is the Shiva Ganga Gardens. The fort still conveys the strength and grandeur that it must have once held, despite being largely demolished. Time to visit:7:00 AM - 1:00 PM & 3:00 PM - 6:00 PM 4. Airavatesvara Temple Among the many Shiva temples in Thanjavur is the Airavatesvara temple, which is situated near Darasuram. According to tradition, Lord Indra's white elephant, Airavata, came here to pray to Lord Shiva in order to lift a curse placed on him by Rishi Durvasa. Yama, the god of death, is claimed to have worshipped Shiva here as well. This temple, along with everyone else at Thanjavur, is regarded as one of the greatest Chola temples still in existence. Timing to visit:6:00 am to 8:00 pm 5. Thanjai Mamani Koil A Divyadesam is a collective name for the trio of Vishnu temples that make up Thanjai Mamani Koil. It is claimed that Lord Vishnu is primarily revered in this location in the form of his Narasimha avatar, which he adopted in order to defeat the devil king Hiranyakashipu and save his disciple Prahlad. Within the temple are their statues. The worshippers of Vishnu love and frequent this temple. Being one of the 108 Divyadesams, the temple attracts worshippers in a unique way and has a unique image. Timing to visit:7 AM to 12:00 PM, 5 PM to 7:30 PM. 6. Schwartz Church Schwartz Church, also recognized as Fort Church, is situated close to Brihadeeswarar Temple in the Thanjavur Palace garden just north of the Sivaganga Tank and was constructed by Raja Serfoji in 1779 as a tribute to his teacher, the Danish missionary FC Schwartz, who passed away in 1798. It is spread over an area of 2 km from Thanjavur Railway Station, 750 km from Old Bus Station, and 500 meters from Brihadeeswarar Temple. Serfoji II, the Maratha ruler, contributed a stunning piece of white marble created by John Flaxman after Schwartz passed away in 1798. This may be seen at the western end of the Schwartz Church. The dying missionary blessing King Serfoji while his ministers accompany him while his ministers surround him is depicted in etching on the marble object. Timing to visit:9:00 AM - 1:00 PM & 2:00 PM - 5:00 PM 7. Thanjavur Royal Palace Considered to be the Nayak Kings' home, it was located inside the Vijaynagara Fort complex. There are numerous locations worth seeing on the palace grounds, including the Nayak Hall, Saraswati Mahal Library, and the Durbar 